# React Testing Patterns (Testing Library)

## Base Structure

```tsx
import { render, screen } from "@testing-library/react";
import userEvent from "@testing-library/user-event";
import { Button } from "./Button";

describe("Button", () => {
  it("renders with correct text", () => {
    render(<Button>Save</Button>);
    expect(screen.getByRole("button", { name: "Save" })).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  it("calls onClick when clicked", async () => {
    const user = userEvent.setup();
    const onClick = vi.fn();
    render(<Button onClick={onClick}>Save</Button>);

    await user.click(screen.getByRole("button"));
    expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalledOnce();
  });
});
```

## Queries (priority order)

1. `getByRole` тАФ preferred (accessibility)
2. `getByLabelText` тАФ for form fields
3. `getByPlaceholderText` тАФ alternative for inputs
4. `getByText` тАФ for visible text
5. `getByTestId` тАФ last resort

## Async Patterns

```tsx
import { render, screen, waitFor } from "@testing-library/react";

it("displays data after loading", async () => {
  render(<UserList />);

  expect(screen.getByText("Loading...")).toBeInTheDocument();
  await waitFor(() => {
    expect(screen.getByText("Maria")).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

## within тАФ Scoped Queries

```tsx
import { within } from "@testing-library/react";

const row = screen.getByRole("row", { name: /maria/i });
expect(within(row).getByText("Active")).toBeInTheDocument();
```

## Conventions

- Use `userEvent` (never `fireEvent`) for interactions
- Always call `userEvent.setup()` before render
- Query by role/label first, `data-testid` as last resort
- Test behavior, not implementation details
- One main `expect` per test (auxiliary asserts are ok)
